  "text": "While these studies found non-pecuniary workplace and job characteristics to influence the labor supply elasticity, the question of the extent to which they impact labor supply decisions was first analyzed by Di Tommaso et al. [CITATION_1] who explicitly modeled Norwegian nurses' shift type (daytime or shift work) and workplace setting (hospital and primary care) choices in a multi-sector labor supply framework. Their main findings were that whilst nurses' labor supply is relatively inelastic with respect to wage as in previous studies, nurses' labor supply is far more responsive to shift work type and workplace setting. Following in the spirit of Di Tommaso et al., a more recent study estimated a structural multi-sector model of nurses' labor supply in different occupations to explicitly account for the entry and exit decisions in and out of the nursing profession in relation to other occupations as well as investigating choice of shift work type [CITATION_2] . The results also suggest that nurses' labor supply may be more responsive to changes in wages than previously thought when allowing for entry and exit into and out of the profession as a consequence of wage changes. The labor supply elasticity is found to vary across shifttypes as in Di Tommaso et al. [CITATION_3] . However, unlike Di Tommaso et al. [CITATION_4] , the authors argue that offering wage differentials across shift types to reduce nurse shortages may lead to movements across shift types from existing nursing stock rather than attracting nurses working outside the profession.",
